text.section:
The Administrative Regulation Review Subcommittee shall:
Conduct a continuous study as to whether additional legislation or changes in legislation are needed based on various factors, including, but not limited to, review of new, emergency, and existing administrative regulations, the lack of administrative regulations, and the needs of administrative bodies;
Except as provided by KRS 158.6471 and 158.6472, review and comment upon administrative regulations submitted to it by the Commission;
Make recommendations for changes in statutes, new statutes, repeal of statutes affecting administrative regulations or the ability of administrative bodies to promulgate them; and
Conduct such other studies relating to administrative regulations as may be assigned by the Commission.

The subcommittee may make a nonbinding determination:
That an administrative regulation is deficient because it:
Is wrongfully promulgated;
Appears to be in conflict with an existing statute;
Appears to have no statutory authority for its promulgation;
Appears to impose stricter or more burdensome state requirements than required by the federal mandate, without reasonable justification;
Fails to use tiering when tiering is applicable;
Is in excess of the administrative body's authority;
Appears to impose an unreasonable burden on government or small business, or both; or
Appears to be deficient in any other manner;
That an administrative regulation is needed to implement an existing statute; or
That an administrative regulation should be amended or repealed.
